WEBVTT

NOTE Approximate draft captions from v3 transcript. Not synchronized to actual narration.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.794
A good AI answer can still arrive too early.

00:00:03.874 --> 00:00:11.462
You ask a question. The model gives you a
fluent paragraph, a clean plan, maybe even a reasonable

00:00:11.542 --> 00:00:13.650
recommendation. It feels like progress.

00:00:13.730 --> 00:00:19.632
But sometimes the answer is solving a question you
have not actually finished asking.

00:00:19.712 --> 00:00:27.300
This video is about slowing the first answer down
just enough to keep the human parts of the

00:00:27.380 --> 00:00:29.180
decision visible.

00:00:29.260 --> 00:00:36.849
By the end, you will have one prompt you
can reuse before any important AI answer. It checks

00:00:36.929 --> 00:00:38.729
three things:

00:00:38.809 --> 00:00:40.609
Goal. Grounding. Ownership.

00:00:40.689 --> 00:00:48.277
What are we trying to do? What facts would
change the answer? And what parts are still mine

00:00:48.357 --> 00:00:50.157
to choose?

00:00:50.237 --> 00:00:57.825
Think of the model as a bright worktable. It
can lay out options, tradeoffs, and missing questions. But

00:00:57.905 --> 00:01:02.121
the worktable should not decide what the work is
for.

00:01:02.201 --> 00:01:04.309
Here is a clean example.

00:01:04.389 --> 00:01:06.189
You ask:

00:01:06.269 --> 00:01:08.798
Should I redesign this onboarding page?

00:01:08.878 --> 00:01:14.780
The model might answer instantly: simplify the page, reduce
friction, test a clearer button.

00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:17.811
Some of that advice might be useful.

00:01:17.891 --> 00:01:20.842
It is also answering a half-built question.

00:01:20.922 --> 00:01:27.667
Does “better” mean more signups? Fewer confused users? Fewer
support tickets? A more honest first impression?

00:01:27.747 --> 00:01:35.335
Those are different goals. If you do not name
the goal, the model may quietly name it for

00:01:35.415 --> 00:01:37.215
you.

00:01:37.295 --> 00:01:39.825
So the first checkpoint is Goal.

00:01:39.905 --> 00:01:45.807
Before asking for advice, ask: what am I actually
trying to decide or create?

00:01:45.887 --> 00:01:52.632
Not just “make this better.” Better for whom? Better
by what measure? Better at what cost?

00:01:52.712 --> 00:01:54.820
A stronger request might say:

00:01:54.900 --> 00:02:02.488
I am deciding whether to redesign an onboarding page.
The goal is not just more signups. It is

00:02:02.568 --> 00:02:10.156
more new users who understand the product and are
less likely to need support in the first week.

00:02:10.236 --> 00:02:17.403
Now the model has a scoreboard. It can still
help, but it is not inventing the game.

00:02:17.483 --> 00:02:19.591
The second checkpoint is Grounding.

00:02:19.671 --> 00:02:23.043
Ask: what real-world facts would change the answer?

00:02:23.123 --> 00:02:29.025
If the model recommends a redesign, what would make
that recommendation stronger or weaker?

00:02:29.105 --> 00:02:36.693
Maybe users drop off at the second step. Maybe
support tickets keep mentioning the same confusing sentence. Maybe

00:02:36.773 --> 00:02:40.146
recordings show people hesitating over a price detail.

00:02:40.226 --> 00:02:44.863
Or maybe the page is not the real problem
at all.

00:02:44.943 --> 00:02:49.159
So instead of only asking, “explain your reasoning,” try
asking:

00:02:49.239 --> 00:02:55.562
What evidence would change your recommendation? Separate what you
know from what you are assuming.

00:02:55.642 --> 00:02:59.436
That turns the answer into a checklist for reality.

00:02:59.516 --> 00:03:03.311
This is a small habit, not a safety guarantee.

00:03:03.391 --> 00:03:09.293
Decision-support researchers have long studied cases where people lean
too hard on automated recommendations.

00:03:09.373 --> 00:03:16.961
In some human-AI studies, explanations changed how people relied
on a system. They did not reliably help people

00:03:17.041 --> 00:03:19.149
spot which recommendations were correct.

00:03:19.229 --> 00:03:23.866
So the point is not: ask for an explanation
and relax.

00:03:23.946 --> 00:03:31.113
The point is: make the goal, assumptions, evidence, and
value choices visible before the advice feels settled.

00:03:31.193 --> 00:03:33.300
The third checkpoint is Ownership.

00:03:33.380 --> 00:03:40.969
Some parts of a decision are not facts the
model can discover. They depend on values, context, responsibility,

00:03:41.049 --> 00:03:42.849
and risk.

00:03:42.929 --> 00:03:50.517
For the onboarding page, maybe a shorter version increases
signups but gives people a less accurate expectation. Maybe

00:03:50.597 --> 00:03:58.185
a clearer page filters out some users but creates
more trust. A model can describe that tradeoff. It

00:03:58.265 --> 00:04:02.481
cannot decide what kind of relationship you want with
users.

00:04:02.561 --> 00:04:06.776
The same idea shows up in a more everyday
situation.

00:04:06.856 --> 00:04:08.656
Suppose you write:

00:04:08.736 --> 00:04:14.638
Draft an email telling a collaborator I am unhappy
that the timeline is slipping.

00:04:14.718 --> 00:04:21.885
The model can produce a polished email. But it
does not know what you want to protect.

00:04:21.965 --> 00:04:29.553
Do you want to repair trust? Set a boundary?
Get a new date? Document accountability? Lower the temperature?

00:04:29.633 --> 00:04:32.163
Make the seriousness impossible to miss?

00:04:32.243 --> 00:04:34.043
Those are different choices.

00:04:34.123 --> 00:04:41.711
A gentle version may preserve warmth but blur the
boundary. A firm version may create clarity but raise

00:04:41.791 --> 00:04:46.850
the temperature. A direct version may do both, depending
on the relationship.

00:04:46.930 --> 00:04:54.518
The model can show versions. It can put the
options side by side. You choose what you are

00:04:54.598 --> 00:04:56.398
willing to stand behind.

00:04:56.478 --> 00:04:58.278
A better request is:

00:04:58.358 --> 00:05:05.946
Before drafting, list the possible goals of this message
and the relationship risks of each. Then give three

00:05:06.026 --> 00:05:10.664
versions: gentle, direct, and firm. Separate tone choices from
factual claims.

00:05:10.744 --> 00:05:17.489
Now the model is doing work on the table.
You are still responsible for the decision.

00:05:17.569 --> 00:05:20.941
Here is the whole habit as one prompt:

00:05:21.021 --> 00:05:28.609
Before answering, help me keep ownership of this decision.
> 1. Restate the goal you think I am

00:05:28.689 --> 00:05:36.278
pursuing. 2. List the facts or evidence that would
change your answer. 3. Identify which parts depend on

00:05:36.358 --> 00:05:42.260
my values, context, or risk tolerance. > Then give
advice, separating assumptions from recommendations.

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:45.291
That does not make the model correct.

00:05:45.371 --> 00:05:48.743
But it gives you three places to intervene.

00:05:48.823 --> 00:05:51.774
If the goal is wrong, correct it.

00:05:51.854 --> 00:05:55.648
If the evidence is missing, go look for it.

00:05:55.728 --> 00:06:01.630
If the answer depends on values, stop pretending it
is only a technical question.

00:06:01.710 --> 00:06:05.926
Try it on the next AI request that actually
matters.

00:06:06.006 --> 00:06:13.594
Paste the prompt before your question. Let the model
fill in the goal, the evidence, and the value-dependent

00:06:13.674 --> 00:06:15.474
parts.

00:06:15.554 --> 00:06:21.456
Then do the important step: edit those three answers
before you accept the recommendation.

00:06:21.536 --> 00:06:25.752
If the model restates the wrong goal, fix the
goal.

00:06:25.832 --> 00:06:33.420
If it lists evidence you do not have, decide
whether to look for that evidence or lower your

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:35.300
confidence.

00:06:35.380 --> 00:06:42.968
If the choice depends on values, context, or risk
tolerance, pause. Smooth prose cannot choose that for you.

00:06:43.048 --> 00:06:50.636
That is the difference between using AI to think
with you and letting it quietly finish the thinking

00:06:50.716 --> 00:06:52.516
for you.

00:06:52.596 --> 00:06:55.547
The point is not to think alone.

00:06:55.627 --> 00:07:03.216
A good model can widen the room: more options,
clearer tradeoffs, sharper questions, and a second pass on

00:07:03.296 --> 00:07:05.096
your reasoning.

00:07:05.176 --> 00:07:06.976
Use it for that.

00:07:07.056 --> 00:07:13.379
Use the model for options and tradeoffs. Keep the
goal, evidence, and final judgment visible.

00:07:13.459 --> 00:07:15.989
Before you accept the answer, ask:

00:07:16.069 --> 00:07:17.869
What is the goal?

00:07:17.949 --> 00:07:20.478
What would ground this in reality?

00:07:20.558 --> 00:07:23.087
What belongs to me to choose?

00:07:23.167 --> 00:07:29.913
Let the AI help you see more. Do not
let it decide what seeing is for.
